`.` is the root of a Rust reimplementation of a TypeScript steno-theory
compiler: it turns `dict.steno` (the canonical DSL source, strict
fenced-block grammar) into four generated artifacts under `out/` — two
Plover dictionaries and two Neovim-plugin tables — via the pipeline
exposed from `crates/steno`. Depending on this repo means either running
one of its three binaries (`build`, `build-nvim`, `measure`) or
`require`-ing the `nvim/` Lua plugin against the JSON it produces;
nothing else is a supported integration point.

The load-bearing coupling spans four places that must move together:
`dict.steno`'s directive/operator grammar, `docs/steno-format.md`'s
description of that grammar, `crates/steno/src/parse.rs`'s implementation
of it, and `viz/index.html`'s hand-copied stroke-layout/one-liner-toggle
logic — none of these three doc/copy locations are enforced against the
code automatically, so a grammar or stroke-layout change made in one and
not the others silently breaks parsing, docs, or the visualizer. `docs/`
is the pre-commit spec layer (grammar, pass-order/error taxonomy, and
pinned TS-vs-Rust precedent); `crates/steno` is the only place that
compiles it; `scripts/ci.sh` gates every push/PR against static checks
(fmt/clippy/deny/machete plus repo-local rationale/lint/cycle checks) and
is the single list of what CI enforces; `.github/workflows` is what
invokes `ci.sh`; `nvim/` and `viz/` are the two independent consumers of
generated JSON, one a live editor plugin, one a static human-facing
inspector.

Invariant holding across the whole tree: dataflow is one-way (stroke ←
parse ← expand ← {editor, render, snippet, blocks}), `dict.steno` is
read-only source of truth never mutated by tests or tooling, and no
runtime/network/async/unsafe dependency exists anywhere — `Cargo.lock`
confirms zero external dependencies are currently locked. A typical
cross-cutting change starts in `dict.steno` + `docs/steno-format.md`
together, then propagates into `crates/steno/src/parse.rs` and, if stroke
layout is involved, into `viz/index.html`.

`crates/` holds the one compiled artifact; `docs/` is its spec;
`scripts/`+`.github/` are the CI gate; `nvim/` and `viz/` are the two
consumers; `dict.steno` is the shared source data; `Cargo.lock` reflects
the zero-dependency policy.